```typescript
const policy = new aws.iam.Policy("kmsDecryptPolicy", {
    policy: JSON.stringify({
        "Version": "2012-10-17",
        "Statement": [
          {
            "Action": "kms:*",
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:kms:us-west-2:153052954103:key/1a0f1f7d-d96e-4651-914c-e5e99672b362"
          }
        ]
      })
});

const api = new serverless.apigateway.API("api", {
    routes: [{
        method: "GET",
        path: "/",
        handler: createLambdaFunction("get-handler", async (req, res) => {
            return {
                statusCode: 200,
                body: "hello",
            }
        }, undefined, {
            policies: [aws.iam.AWSLambdaFullAccess, /* what do I put here? */]
        }),
    }]
});
```

Today, the `policies` array is typed as `ARN[]`, because it ends up getting passed into `aws.serverless.FunctionOptions`, and that value is flown into the name of the role policy attachment we create.

Now, you can imagine us inverting this.  If the `api` object returned allowed me to get access to the `role` that was created, I could manually construct the role policy attachment object myself at the same level where I define the policy and api itself.  But I'd still have the problem of understanding what name I give to the resource, and the comment here: https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi-aws/blob/master/overlays/nodejs/serverless/function.ts#L136-L138 implies that I need to involve the actual ARN itself (which puts be back to square one).

> This would for example make the identity of the resource un-knowable during preview. This is mostly equivalent to creating a resource inside an apply (and in fact, that's a way of working around this).

And I suppose in this case it's on me to ensure that every resource I create in the apply explicitly sets `DependsOn` for every logically captured resource, are there other things I need to watch out for?

```python
@ray.remote
class Foo:
